  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 31.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whose name he called",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is badly translated; it should he, he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gave him the name of Abimelech - literally",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he set his name Abimelech.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " There are two phrases in Hebrew. The one, he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "called his name",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Seth, Noah, Ishmael, Isaac, Esau, Jacob, etc., as the case may be. And this is the phrase always, though not exclusively (see, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 35:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 6:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), used of the name given to a child at its birth or circumcision. The other is, he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gave",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "set him the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " name, or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he gave",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "set his name",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " so-and-so, and this phrase is only used of additional names, or surnames given later in life. The examples are Judges 13:31; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 2:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
